result:
Safe in the common case, dangerous on the tail. Two real concerns:

1. **Pool starvation under big carts.** If a cart has 50 SKUs, that one request grabs 20 connections and queues the other 30. Your other in-flight requests (other orders, anything else hitting the DB) wait behind it. Under concurrent traffic — say 5 simultaneous orders of 30 SKUs each — you have 150 acquisitions fighting over 20 slots. Most pool libs queue with a timeout (pg-pool default is no timeout, knex is 60s); when that timeout fires, you get acquire errors that look nothing like the original code.
2. **Latency hides the smell.** With small carts (3-5 items) it'll work fine in dev and staging and only break for your B2B customer with 200 SKUs. Classic "works until it doesn't."

The right fix isn't to bound the Promise.all concurrency with `p-limit` — it's to **not do N queries in the first place**. One `WHERE sku IN (...)` query takes one connection, one round trip, and is faster than even the best-case parallel version:

```js
const rows = await db.query(
  'SELECT sku, stock FROM inventory WHERE sku = ANY($1)',
  [skus]
);
const bySku = new Map(rows.map(r => [r.sku, r.stock]));
```

Promise.all over per-row queries is almost always the wrong shape — it's parallelism papering over an N+1. Flag it in the review and ask the author to batch the query. If there's some reason a single query won't work (different tables, different shards), then `p-limit(5)` or similar to keep one request from monopolizing the pool, but that's the fallback, not the default.

Bonus check: does the inventory check happen *inside* a transaction? If so, all those parallel queries are trying to use the same connection (transactions are connection-bound), and Promise.all there is actively broken — it'll either serialize anyway or throw depending on the driver.

